udd ap Philip于大约1362年出生在英国时，他的父亲Philip Ap Jenkin Herbert34岁，母亲Alicia36岁。他于大约1401年与Miss ferch Dafydd结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。"},"hr":{"about 1362–":"oko 1362.–preminuo","1356–1438":"1356–1438","1362–Male":"1362–preminuo","–Male":"preminuo","1362–Female":"1362–preminula","1392–1454":"1392.–1454","1330–1387":"1330–1387","1327–Female":"1327–preminula","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","Abt 1357":"oko 1357.","1382":"1382","1392":"1392.","1327":"1327","1455":"1455","1356":"1356","1454":"1454","1387":"1387","about 1401":"oko 1401.","about 1362":"oko 1362.","1438":"1438","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wernddu, Monmouthshire, England":"Engleska, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"cs":{"about 1362–":"okolo 1362–Zesnulý","1356–1438":"1356–1438","1362–Male":"1362–Zesnulý","–Male":"Zesnulý","1362–Female":"1362–Zesnulá","1392–1454":"1392–1454","1330–1387":"1330–1387","1327–Female":"1327–Zesnulá","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","Abt 1357":"okolo 1357","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1327":"1327","1455":"1455","1356":"1356","1454":"1454","1387":"1387","about 1401":"okolo 1401","about 1362":"okolo 1362","1438":"1438","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wernddu, Monmouthshire, England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"about 1362–":"omkring 1362–Afdød","1356–1438":"1356–1438","1362–Male":"1362–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1362–Female":"1362–Afdød","1392–1454":"1392–1454","1330–1387":"1330–1387","1327–Female":"1327–Afdød","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","Abt 1357":"omkring 1357","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1327":"1327","1455":"1455","1356":"1356","1454":"1454","1387":"1387","about 1401":"omkring 1401","about 1362":"omkring 1362","1438":"1438","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wernddu, Monmouthshire, England":"England, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"nl":{"about 1362–":"circa 1362–Overleden","1356–1438":"1356–1438","1362–Male":"1362–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1362–Female":"1362–Overleden","1392–1454":"1392–1454","1330–1387":"1330–1387","1327–Female":"1327–Overleden","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","Abt 1357":"circa 1357","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1327":"1327","1455":"1455","1356":"1356","1454":"1454","1387":"1387","about 1401":"circa 1401","about 1362":"circa 1362","1438":"1438","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wernddu, Monmouthshire, England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1362–":"about 1362–Deceased","1356–1438":"1356–1438","1362–Male":"1362–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1362–Female":"1362–Deceased","1392–1454":"1392–1454","1330–1387":"1330–1387","1327–Female":"1327–Deceased","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","Abt 1357":"about 1357","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1327":"1327","1455":"1455","1356":"1356","1454":"1454","1387":"1387","about 1401":"about 1401","about 1362":"about 1362","1438":"1438","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wernddu, Monmouthshire, England":"England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Philip","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Varughese, Mathai, Babu, Reji, Anil, Binu, Neena, Prema, Raju, Reena, Susheela, Aleykutty.","Scottish, English, German, Dutch, and Jewish: from the Greek personal name <i>Philippos</i> (from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’). In the New Testament this name is borne by one of the apostles; it was also borne by various other early Christian saints. It owes part of its popularity to the medieval romances about Alexander the Great, whose father was Philip of Macedon. As a Jewish name, it represents a borrowing of the personal name from Christians. As a Highland Scottish surname, it represents an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhilib</b> ‘son of Philip’. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Spanish   Felipe  , Catalan <b>Felip</b>, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian or Croatian   Filip  , Albanian   Filipi  , and their derivatives (see examples at   Philips  ). The name <i>Philip</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Philipose   and   Pothen  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Phillip  .","French (southern) and Breton (Finistère): variant of   Philippe  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McKillip","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhilib</b> ‘son of Philip’ (see   Philip  ). See also   McPhillips  ."]},{"name":"Felipe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Juana, Miguel, Orlando, Pedro, Angel, Carlos, Emilio, Jesus.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Felipe</i>, an equivalent of   Philippe  ."]},{"name":"Lips","meanings":["North German, Flemish, and Dutch: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Philips</i>, from Latin <i>Philippus</i> (see   Philip  )."]},{"name":"Lipps","meanings":["North German: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Philipps</i>, from Latin <i>Philippus</i> (see   Philip  )."]},{"name":"Pepin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Camille, Emile, Pierre, Gilles, Lucien, Normand, Alcide, Fernand, Jacques, Marcel.","French (<b>Pépin</b>) and English: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Pipin</i>, of uncertain, probably onomatopoeic origin. The name was borne by several Frankish kings, most notably Pepin le Bref, father of Charlemagne, and remained popular throughout the early Middle Ages.","English: from the unrecorded Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal names <i>Pipin</i>, <i>Pepin</i>, <i>Pipun</i>, pet forms of   Philip  . Compare   Pipe  ."]},{"name":"Lippens","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alfons, Alphons.  French Andre.","Flemish and Dutch: patronymic from a shortened form of the personal name   Philip  ."]},{"name":"Philbin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Philbín</b>, ‘son of Philbin (Irish <i>Philbín</i> or <i>Filibín</i>)’, a pet form of   Philip  ."]},{"name":"Lipman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Mayer, Chaim, Dov, Isadore, Jakob, Meyer, Pinchas.","Dutch: habitational name from a farm named Lipman or perhaps Lippink, referring to a certain <i>Lippo</i> and his kin. <i>Lippo</i> is a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name composed with the element <i>leiba</i> ‘offspring, son’, or of the personal name   Philip  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish personal name <i>Lipman</i>, derived from Middle High German words <i>liep</i> ‘dear, beloved’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Philipose","meanings":["Indian (Kerala): from the personal name <i>Philipose</i>, derived from Greek <i>Philippos</i> (see   Philip  ), found among Christians in southern India. — Note: Since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, this name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]},{"name":"Philibert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Fernand, Mirielle, Pascale, Pierrot.","French: from the personal name <i>Philibert</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Filuberht</i>, composed of the elements <i>fila</i> ‘much, very’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright’, which was borne by a 7th-century Christian saint, abbot of Jumièges. The spelling has been influenced by personal names of Greek origin based on <i>philein</i> ‘to love’, e.g.   Philip  ."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":20,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":93,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Gruffudd